text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Essential: {Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity$:essential}%0a:Title: Dative presentatives in Kentucky English and derivatives%0a:Author: TimG%0a:Section: B%0a:Completed: 10.04.2021 - 17:17%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210421-180422-769730#%0a* [-21.04.2021 - 11:04-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210421-180422-769730#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHere's you a short article on dative presentatives%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe presentative, as discussed in the Yale article (1), is the "Here" in the sentence "Here is the pizza." The idea is to present something to a participant in the conversation. The dative is a pronoun or pronoun phrase. Thus, the dative presentative looks something like this: "Here's you the whole pizza," specifically denoting the person being presented the pizza.%0a%0aThe dative can be first, second, or third person, as well as an actual name, although not every speaker of a dialect which accepts some of these datives after the presentative accepts all of them. It can be used in questions as well, such as "Where's me a pizza," which is a very good question. The Yale database suggests that this language construction is most readily accepted in the American South, where the Kentucky dialect of English was most likely to spread.%0a %0a1. https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/dative-presentatives%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
